          "text": "Yes, orphaning is possible in a few scenarios. Here's the analysis:\n\n**What protects against orphans (happy path):**\n- `before-quit` handler calls `daemonManager.stop()`, which sends SIGTERM then SIGKILL after a timeout\n- The daemon is spawned as a **child process** (not `detached`), so normally the OS will deliver SIGHUP when the parent exits\n\n**Scenarios where orphaning CAN happen:**\n\n1. **Desktop crashes/SIGKILL**: If Electron is killed with SIGKILL (or segfaults), the `before-quit` handler never runs. Since the daemon is spawned **without `detached: true`**, on POSIX systems the OS should send SIGHUP to the child -- but the daemon would need to handle SIGHUP to exit cleanly. If it ignores or doesn't handle SIGHUP, it survives as an orphan (re-parented to PID 1/launchd).\n\n2. **`before-quit` timeout race**: The handler has a 10s force-quit timeout (`app.exit(0)`), but `daemonManager.stop()` itself has its own `DAEMON_SHUTDOWN_TIMEOUT_MS` for SIGTERM->SIGKILL escalation. If `stop()` hangs before even sending SIGTERM (e.g., blocked on something), `app.exit(0)` fires but that's a hard exit -- the daemon process may still be alive.\n\n3. **`stdio: 'inherit'` pipe break**: The daemon inherits stdout/stderr from Electron. When Electron exits, those pipes break. If the daemon doesn't crash on broken pipe writes, it keeps running.\n\n4. **No PID file or port-based liveness check on startup**: When `DaemonManager.start()` runs, it spawns a new daemon without first checking if an old one is already listening on the port. An orphaned daemon from a previous session could be holding the port, causing the new spawn to fail or creating two daemons.\n\n**The most likely real-world orphan scenario** is #1 -- a force-quit or crash of the desktop app where the `before-quit` handler doesn't execute. The daemon has no self-terminating watchdog (e.g., \"exit if my parent PID dies\") to protect against this.",
